<!-- Per MOS:BOLDTITLE and WP:SBE, neither the article's title nor related text appears in bold. -->{{As of|2012|September|24}}, a [[cholera]] outbreak in [[Sierra Leone]] has caused the deaths of 392 people.<ref name=irin24912>{{cite news|title=GUINEA-SIERRA LEONE: Cholera outbreak easing|url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report/96379/GUINEA-SIERRA-LEONE-Cholera-outbreak-easing|accessdate=24 September 2012|newspaper=IRIN|date=24 September 2012|location=Dakar}}</ref> It is the country's worst outbreak of cholera in 15 years.<ref name="telegraph">{{cite news|title=Sierra Leone battles worst cholera outbreak in 15 years|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/sierraleone/9507802/Sierra-Leone-battles-worst-cholera-outbreak-in-15-years.html|accessdate=31 August 2012|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=30 August 2012}}</ref> The outbreak has also affected [[Guinea]],<ref name=irin31/> which shares a reservoir near the coast.<ref name=msf208>{{cite web|title=Guinea and Sierra Leone: Cholera epidemic escalates|url=http://www.msf.org/msf/articles/2012/08/guinea-and-sierra-leone-cholera-epidemic-escalates.cfm|publisher=MSF|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=20 August 2012}}</ref> This is the largest cholera outbreak in Africa in 2012.<ref name=lisa>{{cite news|last=Schlein|first=Lisa|title=Sierra Leone's Cholera Epidemic Easing But Not Over|url=http://www.voanews.com/content/cholera-epidemic-in-sierra-leone-easing-but-not-over/1511745.html|accessdate=22 September 2012|newspaper=Voice of America|date=20 September 2012}}</ref>

Abdulai Bayraytay, the spokesman of the Sierra Leonean government, stated that as of 1 October 2012 there was no new reported cases of cholera.<ref name=ctimes>{{cite news|title=Sierra Leone: 'No New Cholera Cases' - Abdulai Bayraytay Affirms|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201210111211.html|accessdate=11 October 2012|newspaper=Concord Times|date=11 October 2012|author=Memunatu Bangura|author2=Florence Turay}}</ref>

==Source==
Cholera is a [[Waterborne diseases|water-borne disease]], primarily spread by the consumption of water or food contaminated by the [[feces]] of an infected person. The outbreak was triggered by heavy rainfall and flooding in Sierra Leone and Guinea, combined with poor hygiene practices, unsafe water sources, and ineffective waste management.<ref name=irin31>{{cite news|title=GUINEA-SIERRA LEONE: Cholera - rising with the downpours|url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report/96212/GUINEA-SIERRA-LEONE-Cholera-rising-with-the-downpours|accessdate=31 August 2012|newspaper=IRIN Africa|date=31 August 2012|location=Freetown}}</ref><ref name=bbc25>{{cite news|title=UK to spend Â£2m combating cholera in Sierra Leone|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-19377113|accessdate=31 August 2012|newspaper=BBC|date=25 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=nathnac/> Crowded living conditions, poor sanitation and inadequate access to safe water are responsible for the higher rates of the outbreak in the [[Western Area]] including [[Freetown]], the capital of Sierra Leone.<ref name=nathnac/>

Only about 40% of people in Sierra Leone have access to a private or shared [[latrine]], where approximately seven families typically share one toilet.<ref name=tlive/> According to ''The Africa Review'', nearly 60% of toilets are [[pit toilet]]s that easily drain directly into sources of drinking water<ref name=care217/> and more than 30% of people defecate in the open.<ref name=arev/> The water and sanitation systems were damaged after [[Sierra Leone Civil War|the civil war]] in Sierra Leone, and have not been rebuilt properly, leaving approximately 43% of Sierra Leoneans without access to clean water.<ref name=tlive/><ref name=care217/> Poor health-care system in the country with the population of six million people also contributes to the outbreak. The UN figures indicate that there is only one doctor per 34,744 people.<ref name=aljaz16>{{cite news|title=Sierra Leone hit by cholera outbreak|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/africa/2012/08/2012816173953690645.html|accessdate=1 September 2012|newspaper=Al Jazeera|date=16 August 2012}}</ref>

==Casualties==
The disease has killed 392 people and infected more than 25,000 others in Sierra Leone and Guinea since February 2012, when the epidemic was reported.<ref name=irin24912/> On 4 September 2012, the death toll increased to 350.<ref name=alertreu/> On 12 September, Dr. Amara Jambai, the Director of Disease Surveillance and Control in the Ministry of Health and Sanitation, reported that cholera infection in Sierra Leone dropped as a result of the activities of the government and other organizations.<ref name=slgov>{{cite web|title=Sierra Leone: Cholera Infection Drops|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201209130470.html|publisher=Sierra Leone Government|accessdate=13 September 2012|location=Freetown|date=12 September 2012}}</ref> 

For the period of January to mid-August 2012, more than 11,600 cholera cases were officially recorded by the Ministry of Health and Sanitation in Sierra Leone.<ref name=nytdakar>{{cite news|last=Nossiter|first=Adam|title=Cholera Epidemic Envelops Coastal Slums in West Africa|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/23/world/africa/cholera-epidemic-envelops-coastal-slums-in-west-africa.html|accessdate=1 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 August 2012|agency=AP|location=Dakar}}</ref> By 30 August, reported cases increased to 13,934 according to the [[World Health Organization|World Health Organization (WHO)]].<ref name=rweb>{{cite web|title=Sierra Leone/Guinea: Cholera Outbreak - Feb 2012|url=http://reliefweb.int/disaster/ep-2012-000041-sle|publisher=Relief Web|accessdate=1 September 2012}}</ref> The [[Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs|UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA)]] reported that ten of Sierra Leone's thirteen districts were affected.<ref name=irin31/> The outbreak occurred primarily in eight districts until August 2012:<ref name=alertreu/> [[Port Loko]], [[Kambia District|Kambia]], [[Tonkolili District|Tonkolili]], Bo, [[Moyamba District|Moyamba]], [[Bombali District|Bombali]], [[Pujehun District|Pujehun]] and the Western Area.<ref name=anetreu/> However, twelve districts became affected by the outbreak by September 2012.<ref name=alertreu/>

Of these districts, the one most affected is the Western Area, which includes the capital, Freetown. This area witnessed 4,965 cases and 63 deaths from 1 January to mid-August 2012.<ref name=anetreu>{{cite news|last=Akam|first=Simon|title=Sierra Leone declares cholera outbreak a national emergency|url=http://www.trust.org/alertnet/news/sierra-leone-declares-cholera-outbreak-a-national-emergency|accessdate=31 August 2012|newspaper=Alert Net|date=17 August 2012|agency=Reuters|location=Freetown}}</ref> The number of cases and deaths for Port Loko during the same period is 2,806 and 45, respectively.<ref name=nathnac>{{cite web|title=Cholera outbreak in Sierra Leone|url=http://www.nathnac.org/pro/clinical_updates/cholera_sierra_leone_220812.htm|publisher=NaTHNaC|accessdate=1 September 2012|date=22 August 2012}}</ref> There were 1,134 reported cases and 28 deaths in the Kambala district.<ref name=nathnac/> In Moyamba district nearly 20 people died from the cholera outbreak from 25 July to November 2012.<ref name=ctimes511>{{cite news|title=Sierra Leone: Cholera Kills 20 in Moyamba|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201211051197.html|accessdate=11 November 2012|newspaper=Concord Times|date=5 November 2012|author=Hawa Amara|author2=Florence Turay|location=Free Town}}</ref> At the beginning of August, the disease began to ravage the [[Kenema District|Kenema district]].<ref name=at30812>{{cite news|title=Playing Politics with Cholera in Kenema Sierra Leone?|url=http://news.sl/drwebsite/publish/article_200521014.shtml|accessdate=1 September 2012|newspaper=Awareness Times|date=30 August 2012}}</ref> The Ministry of Health and Sanitation reported that the disease is spreading more rapidly in cities than in isolated areas with poor sanitation.<ref name=care217>{{cite web|last=Vrba|first=Sarah|title=176 Dead in Sierra Leone Cholera Outbreak|url=http://www.care2.com/causes/176-dead-in-sierra-leone-cholera-outbreak.html|publisher=Care2|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=17 August 2012}}</ref> 

On 24 September, OCHA issued a report, indicating that in the period between late August and 16 September, new cholera cases per week decreased from 2,110 to 1,418 in Sierra Leone and from 1,152 to 346 in Guinea.<ref name=irin24912/> According to the data of the [[UN Children's Fund]] (UNICEF) and the World Health Organization, nearly 841 new cases were reported in at the beginning of October 2012.<ref name=irin18>{{cite news|title=Cholera Ebbing in Sierra Leone|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201210191136.html|accessdate=20 October 2012|newspaper=IRIN|date=18 October 2012}}</ref>  It was 433 in the second week of October.<ref name=irin18/>

==State of emergency==
On 17 August 2012, Sierra Leonean [[President of Sierra Leone|President]] [[Ernest Bai Koroma]] announced that the outbreak was a national public health crisis.<ref name=irin31/> At this time the cholera outbreak had a mortality rate of 1.8% in the country, nearly double the threshold for a state of emergency.<ref name=Tinq26>{{cite news|title=Cholera Outbreak Leaves 224 Dead In Sierra Leone|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/312837/cholera-outbreak-leaves-224-dead-in-sierra-leone/|accessdate=1 September 2012|newspaper=The Inquisitr|date=26 August 2012}}</ref> By the end of August 2012, approximately 13,300 people were infected by cholera; humanitarian officials confirmed that 217 had already died by 23 August.<ref name="AFP S Leone"/><ref>[http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A1-8662aa65cae14ca9bd6fb3dcd24cd590.html Sierra Leone cholera death toll rises to 217]. Associated Press, 23 August 2012 {{subscription required|via=[[HighBeam Research]]}}</ref> 
The Sierra Leonean government and WHO predict that 32,000 people will be infected in September due to the rainy season.<ref name=tlive>{{cite news|title=Sierra Leone cholera outbreak worsens as rainy season peaks|url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/africa/2012/08/30/sierra-leone-cholera-outbreak-worsens-as-rainy-season-peaks|accessdate=31 August 2012|newspaper=Times Live|date=30 August 2012|agency=SAPA}}</ref><ref name="AFP S Leone">{{cite web |url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5hkr0oKYgUKYOZaCdIBQ8CYgVHFYg?docId=CNG.9281272cc980979698afae1108f9f7a1.2e1|title=S.Leone cholera outbreak to worsen as rainy season peaks|publisher=AFP| date=29 August 2012|accessdate=31 August 2012|author=Johnson, Rod Mac}}</ref>

==International responses==
In late August 2012, Amanda McClelland, the Emergency Health Coordinator of the [[International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies]], said that the outbreak "has the potential to cause a serious humanitarian crisis" and called for "more funds to deliver the most effective response".<ref name="Red Cross"/>

The [[Government of the United Kingdom|British government]] announced that it allocated Â£2 million for an emergency plan to counter the cholera outbreak in Sierra Leone.<ref name=bbc25/> Additionally, the Rapid Response Facility (RRF) established in March 2012 and activated by the British government is expected to assist Sierra Leone in coping with the epidemic.<ref name=DIHD/><ref name=aafrica298>{{cite news|title=UK Govt Intervenes to Stem Cholera Deaths - Activates New Rapid Response Facility|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201208310164.html|accessdate=31 August 2012|newspaper=All Africa|date=29 August 2012|agency=Concord Times|location=Freetown}}</ref> The facility is a network consisting of private businesses and specialist aid organisations that provide rapid emergency medical, water and sanitation assistance to affected people in the country.<ref name=aafrica298/>

In addition, [[MÃ©decins Sans FrontiÃ¨res|Doctors Without Borders]], in cooperation with the Ministry of Health and Sanitation, runs three cholera treatment units in Freetown, where more than 500 patients have been treated.<ref name=sem3112>{{cite news|title=Battling Cholera in Freetown, Sierra Leone|url=http://www.sierraexpressmedia.com/archives/45456|accessdate=31 August 2012|newspaper=Sierra Express Media|date=31 July 2012}}</ref> The organisation has treated approximately 4,600 patients in Sierra Leone and Guinea since February.<ref name=msf208/> The group has begun to establish other cholera treatment centres at 34 Military Hospital in the west of Freetown, expanding the total number of beds from 90 to 200.<ref name=sem3112/><ref name=nera>{{cite news|title=S.Leone cholera outbreak to worsen as rainy season peaks|url=http://www.newera.com.na/articles/47353/S-Leone-cholera-outbreak-to-worsen-as-rainy-season-peaks|accessdate=31 August 2012|newspaper=New Era|date=31 August 2012}}</ref> The group is also collaborating with the Ministry of Health and Sanitation to inform the public of how to avoid contracting the disease.<ref name=sem3112/> Among the other groups helping victims are Action Firm (AF) and [[Sierra Leone Red Cross Society|the Sierra Leone Red Cross Society]]. AF provided free medical care for victims while about 400 volunteers of the Sierra Leone Red Cross helped out on sanitation awareness campaigns.<ref name=arev>{{cite news|last=Cham|first=Kemo|title=Cholera hits Sierra Leone hard, leaving 100 dead|url=http://www.africareview.com/News/Sierra+Leone+battles+cholera+outbreak/-/979180/1479084/-/e8m3i4/-/index.html|accessdate=31 August 2012|newspaper=Africa Review|date=14 August 2012}}</ref> [[Oxfam]], a charity group based in the United Kingdom, is another group that provides nearly 67,000 people in Freetown with emergency water chlorination.<ref name=oxfam>{{cite web|title=Sierra Leone cholera outbreak|url=http://www.oxfam.org.uk/what-we-do/emergency-response/sierra-leone-cholera|publisher=Oxfam|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> Oxfam also plans to assist up to 500,000 people with cholera prevention kits, water purification kits and public information campaigns on how to prevent the disease.<ref name=oxfam/> [[The Isle of Man]] donated Â£25,000 to assist the activities in the country through Oxfam.<ref name=bbc5912>{{cite news|title=Isle of Man help for Sierra Leone cholera outbreak|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-isle-of-man-19475707|accessdate=5 September 2012|newspaper=BBC|date=4 September 2012}}</ref> The other British groups mobilised include [[Save the Children]], [[International Rescue Committee]], [[Concern Worldwide|Concern]], [[Care International]] and [[British Red Cross|the British Red Cross]].<ref name=DIHD>{{cite web|title=Sierra Leone: UK rapid response to tackle cholera|url=http://www.dfid.gov.uk/News/Latest-news/2012/Sierra-Leone-UK-rapid-response-to-tackle-cholera-outbreak/|publisher=UK Department for International Development|accessdate=1 September 2012|format=Press Release|date=22 August 2012}}</ref> [[Finnish Red Cross|The Finnish Red Cross]] sent medication and doctors to the country on 24 and 25 August.<ref name=tlive/> [[World Vision]] is also working with the government to prevent the disease from spreading through various activities, including the collection of the garbage pills.<ref name=alertreu>{{cite news|title=World Vision responds to Sierra Leone's worst cholera outbreak in more than a decade|url=http://www.trust.org/alertnet/news/world-vision-responds-to-sierra-leones-worst-cholera-outbreak-in-more-than-a-decade|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=Alert Net|date=5 September 2012|agency=Reuters}}</ref> An [[International Centre for Diarrhoeal Disease Research, Bangladesh]] team began its activities in coordination with the WHO in the country on 6 September 2012.<ref name=fe>{{cite news|title=ICDDR,B team reaches Sierra Leone to tackle cholera outbreak|url=http://www.thefinancialexpress-bd.com/more.php?news_id=142523&date=2012-09-07|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Financial Express|date=7 September 2012}}</ref> 

The International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies launched an emergency appeal for $1.14 million in August, explaining that the number of cases of cholera was rising, along with the number of fatal cases.<ref name="Red Cross">{{cite web|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2012/08/23/us-africa-cholera-idUSBRE87M0SR20120823|title=Red Cross fears Sierra Leone cholera crisis, appeals for funds|publisher=Reuters|date=23 August 2012|accessdate=31 August 2012|author=Akam, Simon}}</ref> Tiina Saarikoski of the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Society reported on 30 August that the Bombali, Tonkolili, Port Loko and Kambia districts have been targeted to effectively deal with the epidemic.<ref name=awarenesst>{{cite news|last=Kamara|first=Michael T.|title=More Red Cross Delegates Jet in to Sierra Leone to help Fight Cholera|url=http://news.sl/drwebsite/publish/article_200521011.shtml|accessdate=31 August 2012|newspaper=Awareness Times|date=30 August 2012|location=Freetown}}</ref> The IFRC has funded health promotion activities and assistance to affected families, including the preparation of oral rehydration solutions and construction of suitable toilets, but the organisation has stated that the level of aid coverage remains "very low."<ref name="Red Cross"/>

[[Cholera vaccine|Oral cholera vaccines]] have the potential to shorten cholera outbreaks, and hence reduce the morbidity and mortality associated with outbreaks have not been deployed in Sierra Leone.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reyburn|first=Rita|coauthors=Jacqueline L. Deen, Rebecca F. Grais, Sujit K. Bhattacharya, Dipika Sur, Anna L. Lopez, Mohamed S. Jiddawi, John D. Clemens, and Lorenz von Seidlein|title=The Case for Reactive Mass Oral Cholera Vaccinations|journal=PLoS Negl Trop Dis|year=2011|month=January|doi=10.1371/journal.pntd.0000952|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3026767/|accessdate=6 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=irin13sept12>{{cite news|title=Conakry Residents Demand Cholera Vaccine|url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201209141040.html|accessdate=14 September 2012|newspaper=IRIN|date=13 September 2012}}</ref> The large international institutions IFRC as well WHO have shied away from large mass vaccination campaigns despite the fact that oral cholera vaccines have been successfully used earlier in 2012 by MSF in Guinea Bissau and by Partners in Health in Haiti.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Enserink|first=Martin|title=Policy Shifts on Emergency Use of Cholera Vaccines|journal=Science|date=17 Aug 2012|year=2012|10.1126/science.337.6096.785 |volume=337|pages=785â6|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/337/6096/785.summary|accessdate=6 September 2012}}</ref>

